            <fr:title text="Compounds and components">Compounds and components</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>            Every compound sentence has some number of <html:em>components</html:em>.
            Its components are the sentences used by the main connective in building up the compound sentence.
            As a result, the number of components a compound sentence has is always the same as the arity of its main connective.
</html:p>
            <html:p>            So, for example, all conjunctions have two components; and the components of the conjunction <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  q]]></fr:tex> are <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>.
            To keep track of the order they occur in, we call <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> its <html:strong>left component</html:strong> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex> its <html:strong>right component</html:strong>.
            Every sentence whose main connective is binary has a left component and a right component.
            Let's look at some examples: the right component of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\neg  q \lor  p) \land  \bot ]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex>; the left component of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\neg  q \lor  p) \land  \bot ]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  q \lor  p]]></fr:tex>; and the right component of the left component of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\neg  q \lor  p) \land  \bot ]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex></html:p>
            <html:p>            For sentences whose main connective is unary, there is only one component.
            Here are some examples: the component of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg \neg \neg  (p \lor  q)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg \neg  (p \lor  q)]]></fr:tex>; the component of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  \bot ]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex>; and the left component of the component of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  (\bot  \land  q)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
            <html:p><html:strong>A good idea:</html:strong>Double-check all these examples, so that you can see the idea for yourself!
            Remember, this is <html:em>symbolic</html:em> logic; there are going to be a lot of symbols.
            It's important to build good habits right away---don't let your eyes glaze over this stuff.
            Read carefully; re-read.
</html:p>
            <html:p>            Sentences whose main connective is nullary have 0 components; that is, they don't have any components.
            The same goes for atomic sentences: no components at all.
            Only sentences with a main connective with arity 1 or more have components.
</html:p>
